expected_inputs.hardware_requirements: Cloud-based hosting with minimum 2 vCPUs, 8GB RAM for app servers, AWS RDS for database, and 50GB SSD storage; scalable load balancer configuration for peak loads.
expected_inputs.interaction_interface: Responsive web interface with mobile-first design, intuitive navigation, accessibility compliance (WCAG 2.1), and optimized load times; includes interactive UI elements and seamless database-driven content updates.
expected_inputs.test_optimization_plan: Automated unit and integration testing using Jest and Cypress, load testing with Apache JMeter, continuous performance monitoring via New Relic, and iterative A/B testing for UI/UX refinement.

inputs_used.system_design:
Project goal: Build a scalable, secure, and high-performing website that supports user accounts, content management, search, and optional e-commerce modules, with strong UX and SEO.

High-level architecture (modular monolith or service-oriented):
- Frontend (Web Client): Next.js SSR/SSG for fast loads, routing, and SEO; SPA behavior for dynamic pages.
- Backend (API Layer): NestJS REST (and optional GraphQL) providing services: Auth, User Profiles, Content, Media, Search, Payments, Notifications.
- API Gateway/Ingress: Nginx or Cloud-managed load balancer for routing, rate-limiting, TLS termination.
- Database (Primary): PostgreSQL for relational data with strong ACID guarantees.
- Caching: Redis for sessions, rate limits, frequently accessed content, and queueing.
- Object Storage: S3-compatible storage for images, videos, documents with signed URLs.
- CDN: CloudFront or similar for static assets and media to reduce latency.
- Search: OpenSearch/Elasticsearch for full-text search, faceting, and autocomplete.
- Messaging/Queues: SQS or RabbitMQ for asynchronous tasks (emails, image processing, webhooks).
- Observability: Centralized logging (ELK/OpenSearch), metrics (Prometheus), tracing (OpenTelemetry), and alerts.
- CI/CD: GitHub Actions for build/test/deploy; containerized with Docker; infrastructure as code via Terraform.
- Security: WAF, secrets management (AWS Secrets Manager), OWASP best practices, zero-trust networking, least privilege IAM.

Core backend modules and responsibilities:
- Auth & Identity: OAuth2/OIDC (Auth0/Keycloak), email/password, social login; MFA; password reset; JWT/opaque tokens.
- Users & Profiles: Account management, preferences, avatars, privacy controls.
- CMS: Articles/pages, categories, tags, rich text, media embedding, versioning, drafts, publishing workflows, roles-based access.
- Comments & Reactions: User-generated interactions with moderation tools.
- E-commerce (optional): Products, pricing, inventory, carts, orders, payments (Stripe), refunds.
- Notifications: Email (SES), in-app, push; digest scheduling; templates.
- Search & Discovery: Indexing content/users/products; ranking, synonyms, filters.
- Analytics: Event tracking, funnels; export to data warehouse if needed.

Database design (PostgreSQL):
- users(id PK UUID, email UNIQUE, password_hash, status, created_at, updated_at)
- user_profiles(user_id PK/FK users.id, display_name, bio, avatar_url, locale, timezone)
- roles(id PK, name UNIQUE) and user_roles(user_id FK, role_id FK) for RBAC
- permissions(id PK, key UNIQUE) and role_permissions(role_id FK, permission_id FK) for fine-grained access
- sessions(id PK, user_id FK, refresh_token_hash, expires_at, device_info, ip)
- content(id PK, type ENUM[article,page], title, slug UNIQUE, body_richtext, author_id FK users.id, status ENUM[draft,published,archived], published_at, updated_at)
- categories(id PK, name, slug UNIQUE)
- tags(id PK, name UNIQUE)
- content_categories(content_id FK, category_id FK, PK composite)
- content_tags(content_id FK, tag_id FK, PK composite)
- comments(id PK, content_id FK, parent_comment_id FK NULLABLE, author_id FK, body_text, status ENUM[visible,hidden,flagged], created_at)
- reactions(id PK, content_id FK, user_id FK, type ENUM[like,bookmark,share], created_at)
- media_assets(id PK, owner_id FK users.id, url, type ENUM[image,video,doc], storage_key, metadata JSONB, created_at)
- products(id PK, sku UNIQUE, name, description, price_cents, currency, stock_qty, status)
- carts(id PK, user_id FK, status ENUM[active,converted]) and cart_items(id PK, cart_id FK, product_id FK, qty)
- orders(id PK, user_id FK, total_cents, currency, status ENUM[pending,paid,shipped,refunded], created_at)
- order_items(id PK, order_id FK, product_id FK, price_cents, qty)
- payments(id PK, order_id FK, provider ENUM[stripe], charge_id, status ENUM[succeeded,failed,pending], amount_cents, created_at)
- notifications(id PK, user_id FK, type, channel ENUM[email,inapp,push], payload JSONB, status, created_at)
- audit_logs(id PK, actor_user_id FK, action, target_type, target_id, context JSONB, created_at)
- feature_flags(id PK, key UNIQUE, enabled BOOLEAN, rollout_percentage INT, conditions JSONB)
- ab_tests(id PK, name, status, start_at, end_at) and ab_variants(id PK, test_id FK, key, weight)
- indexes: unique(slug,email,sku); BTREE on foreign keys; GIN on JSONB for metadata; partial indexes for status; full-text indexes on content(title, body) via tsvector.

Search index design (OpenSearch):
- Indices: content_index (id, title, body, tags, categories, author, status), users_index (id, display_name, bio), products_index (id, name, description, price, availability).
- Features: analyzers for stemming, stop words; autocomplete; faceting by category/tag; synonym maps.

Data flows:
- Write path: Backend persists to PostgreSQL, triggers background jobs for indexing media processing, and search index updates.
- Read path: API fetches from PostgreSQL with Redis caching; CDN serves static/media; search queries hit OpenSearch.

Security & compliance:
- Input validation, rate limiting, CSRF protection (where applicable), HTTPS everywhere, content moderation, audit trails.
- GDPR/CCPA: data subject requests, data retention policies, PII encryption at rest and in transit.

Scalability strategy:
- Stateless app instances with horizontal autoscaling; DB read replicas; Redis cluster; sharding not required initially.

Migration & rollout:
- Phased delivery: MVP (auth, CMS, profiles), Phase 2 (comments/search), Phase 3 (e-commerce/analytics), Phase 4 (advanced personalization).
inputs_used.technology_stack:
Frontend: Next.js (React 18), TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, Radix UI, SSR/SSG, i18n (next-intl), form handling (react-hook-form), state (Zustand/Redux Toolkit).
Backend: NestJS (TypeScript), REST + GraphQL (optional), Prisma ORM (PostgreSQL), OpenAPI docs (Swagger), Redis, BullMQ for jobs, Stripe SDK, AWS SDK.
Database: PostgreSQL 15 (RDS), Redis (ElastiCache), OpenSearch, S3-compatible object storage.
Infra/DevOps: Docker, Kubernetes (EKS) or ECS Fargate, Nginx ingress, CloudFront CDN, Terraform IaC, GitHub Actions CI/CD, AWS Secrets Manager, AWS WAF.
Auth: Auth0 or Keycloak (OIDC); JWT/opaque tokens stored in HttpOnly cookies.
Analytics/Monitoring: Plausible or Google Analytics 4, Prometheus/Grafana, OpenTelemetry, ELK/OpenSearch logs, Sentry for error tracking.
Testing: Jest, Supertest (API), Playwright or Cypress (E2E), k6 (load), Lighthouse CI, Semgrep/OWASP ZAP.
inputs_used.hardware_requirements:
No GPU required. Cloud-managed resources with autoscaling.
- Frontend/Backend app nodes: start with 2–3 pods/instances, each 2 vCPU, 4–8 GB RAM; autoscale to 10+ under load.
- Database (PostgreSQL RDS): db.m5.large (2 vCPU, 8 GB RAM) for MVP; scale to db.m5.xlarge (4 vCPU, 16 GB RAM) with read replica.
- Redis: cache.t3.small to start; scale to cache.m5.large as traffic grows.
- OpenSearch: 2 data nodes (r6g.large.search) + 1 master node for small clusters; scale shard count with index size.
- Storage: RDS 100–200 GB GP3; S3 bucket starting at 100 GB with lifecycle policies; EBS volumes for app nodes ~50–100 GB.
- Networking: Managed load balancer (ALB) with TLS certs; WAF enabled.
inputs_used.interaction_interface:
UX goals: fast, intuitive, accessible, and mobile-first.
- Navigation: Clear global nav with breadcrumb trails; contextual sidebars; search prominently placed.
- Performance: SSR for first meaningful paint; image optimization; prefetching; lazy loading; skeleton screens.
- Accessibility (WCAG 2.2 AA): Semantic HTML, proper ARIA, focus states, keyboard navigation, color contrast checks, captions/alt text.
- Personalization: User dashboards, saved content, recommendations powered by search signals and simple collaborative filtering.
- Content authoring: Rich editor with markdown/HTML; media upload with drag-and-drop; autosave drafts; preview; role-based workflows.
- Forms: Inline validation, clear error/success states, auto-complete, progressive disclosure; reCAPTCHA/turnstile to prevent spam.
- Internationalization: i18n routing, locale-aware formatting, RTL support.
- Trust & safety: Clear privacy settings, content reporting, moderation feedback loops.
- SEO: Clean URLs, structured data (JSON-LD), sitemaps, canonical tags, meta tags, Open Graph/Twitter cards.
inputs_used.test_optimization_plan:
Testing strategy:
- Unit tests (Jest) for services/components; >80% coverage on critical paths.
- Integration tests (Supertest) for API endpoints; contract testing for external providers (Stripe/Auth0).
- E2E tests (Playwright/Cypress) for key user journeys (signup, publish content, search, checkout).
- Accessibility tests: axe-core automation + manual audits.
- Security: Semgrep SAST in CI; dependency scanning; OWASP ZAP dynamic testing against staging; secrets detection.
- Performance: Lighthouse CI budgets; Web Vitals (FID, LCP, CLS) monitoring; k6 load tests; caching and DB query profiling.
- Observability: Sentry for errors, Prometheus/Grafana dashboards, alerting SLAs (uptime, response times).
- A/B Testing: Feature flags and AB test framework; run experiments with clear success metrics; rollback safeguards.
- Analytics & Feedback: GA4/Plausible events, heatmaps (optional), user surveys; quarterly UX reviews.
- Release process: Trunk-based development, PR checks, blue/green or canary deployments, automated rollbacks on health check failures.

inputs_used.prompt:
Create a robust, production-ready Python script named complex_analysis.py that automatically analyzes a CSV dataset (default file: complex.csv) and solves the most appropriate problem (classification, regression, or unsupervised clustering/outlier detection). The script should save all outputs under the directory code/complex_dataset_analysis. It must be well-documented, handle edge cases, and provide a clean CLI.

Requirements:
1) General
- Language: Python 3.9+
- Libraries: pandas, numpy, scikit-learn, joblib, scipy, matplotlib (optional), seaborn (optional). Avoid network calls and external services.
- Reproducibility: Use a fixed random_state (e.g., 42) across algorithms.
- CLI using argparse:
  --data_path: Path to CSV (default: complex.csv)
  --target: Optional target column name (default: auto-detect: ['target','label','y'] or heuristic)
  --task: Optional override task type: ['auto','classification','regression','clustering'] (default: 'auto')
  --test_size: Optional test split fraction (default: 0.2)
  --max_categories: Max unique values considered categorical (default: 50)

2) Data loading & EDA
- Load CSV robustly, report shape, columns, dtypes.
- Summarize missing values per column and overall missingness rate.
- Save a brief EDA summary to report.md in code/complex_dataset_analysis.

3) Target detection & task selection
- If --task != 'auto', use specified task.
- Else auto-detect target column:
  - Priority order: user-provided --target; then columns named in ['target','label','y']; else heuristic: consider the last column if its uniqueness ratio < 0.7 or number of unique values <= 20; otherwise treat as unsupervised.
- If a target is found:
  - Determine classification vs regression:
    - Classification when target is object/category or integer with small number of unique levels (<= 20 or <= 5% of rows).
    - Regression when target is float or int with many unique values.
- Handle target missing values (drop rows where target is missing).

4) Preprocessing
- Separate features and target.
- Build a ColumnTransformer:
  - Numeric pipeline: SimpleImputer(strategy='median'), StandardScaler.
  - Categorical pipeline: SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent'), OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore').
- Identify numeric vs categorical columns using pandas dtypes and max_categories threshold.

5) Supervised learning (if target exists)
- Train/test split using the provided test_size.
- Candidate models:
  Classification: LogisticRegression(max_iter=500), RandomForestClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier.
  Regression: LinearRegression, RandomForestRegressor, GradientBoostingRegressor.
- Wrap each model with the preprocessing pipeline (Pipeline with ColumnTransformer).
- Use cross-validation (StratifiedKFold for classification, KFold for regression, n_splits=5) on the training set to select the best model based on:
  - Classification metrics: accuracy, F1 (macro), ROC-AUC (if binary), log loss.
  - Regression metrics: R2 and RMSE.
- Choose the model with the best primary metric (accuracy for classification, R2 for regression), with secondary metrics reported.
- Fit the best model on the full training set; evaluate on the test set; save metrics to metrics.json.
- Generate predictions on the test set; save to predictions.csv including true target and predicted values (and predicted probabilities for classification if available).
- Save trained model and preprocessing pipeline using joblib: model.joblib and preprocessor.joblib.

6) Unsupervised (if no target)
- Clustering (KMeans): Try k in [2..10]; compute silhouette score; choose best k; assign cluster labels; save cluster_labels.csv.
- Outlier detection: IsolationForest; save outliers.csv (rows flagged as anomalies).
- Create a summary of cluster sizes, silhouette score, and example centroids (on scaled numeric features).

7) Reporting
- Compile a report.md with:
  - EDA summary (shape, columns, missingness, basic stats).
  - Task decision logic and result.
  - If supervised: model comparison table (metrics per candidate), best model details, test metrics, feature processing overview.
  - If unsupervised: selected k, silhouette score, cluster size distribution, outlier summary.
- Also save metrics.json (supervised) or clustering_metrics.json (unsupervised) with key metrics.

8) Robustness & UX
- Clear logging with print statements for major steps.
- Gracefully handle errors:
  - Missing file or unreadable CSV.
  - No usable features (e.g., all NaN).
  - Target column invalid or not found.
- If issues occur, write an error section to report.md.

9) File outputs (created at runtime by the script)
- Directory: code/complex_dataset_analysis (create if not exists)
- Files:
  - report.md
  - metrics.json or clustering_metrics.json
  - predictions.csv (supervised)
  - cluster_labels.csv and outliers.csv (unsupervised)
  - model.joblib and preprocessor.joblib (supervised)

10) Structure and readability
- Use main() and helper functions:
  - load_data(path)
  - summarize_eda(df)
  - detect_target_and_task(df, args)
  - build_preprocessor(df, max_categories)
  - train_and_select_model(X, y, task, preprocessor, test_size)
  - run_unsupervised(df, preprocessor)
  - save_reports_and_artifacts(...)
- Include docstrings and type hints.

11) Defaults
- Default data path: complex.csv (in current working directory).
- Default task: auto.

Implement the complete script with the above behavior, ensuring it runs end-to-end without external dependencies beyond the specified libraries, and produces informative outputs for a wide range of complex datasets.

expected_inputs.code:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load climate change dataset (placeholder)
data = pd.read_csv('climate_change_data.csv')

# Prepare features and target
X = np.array(data['Year']).reshape(-1, 1)
y = data['AverageTemperature']

# Train linear regression model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X, y)

# Predict future trends
future_years = np.array(range(2024, 2036)).reshape(-1, 1)
predictions = model.predict(future_years)

# Plot results
plt.plot(data['Year'], y, label='Historical Data')
plt.plot(future_years, predictions, label='Predicted Trend', linestyle='--')

plt.ylabel('Global Average Temperature (°C)')
plt.legend()
plt.savefig('climate_change_projection.png')
print('Climate change model executed successfully. Projection complete.')

inputs_used.prompt:
Write a robust Python script that studies global climate change trends over the past 10 years and forecasts future trends, using authoritative Earth-science datasets. Requirements:

1) Data sources (download programmatically with graceful fallbacks):
   - Global mean surface temperature anomalies (monthly): Prefer NASA GISTEMP v4 table data.
       Primary: https://data.giss.nasa.gov/gistemp/tabledata_v4/Global-mean-monthly.csv
       Fallback: https://data.giss.nasa.gov/gistemp/tabledata_v4/GLB.Ts+dSST.csv
       Notes: These files include Year and monthly columns (Jan..Dec). Values are anomalies (°C) relative to 1951-1980.
   - Atmospheric CO2 (monthly): NOAA Mauna Loa monthly means.
       URL: https://gml.noaa.gov/webdata/ccgg/trends/co2/co2_mm_mlo.csv
       Notes: CSV contains comment lines starting with '#'; columns include year, month, average, seasonally_adjusted. Use seasonally_adjusted when available; fall back to average.

2) Processing:
   - Convert the temperature anomalies table to a monthly time series with Date index (YYYY-MM-01), one value per month.
   - Convert CO2 table to monthly time series (Date index), dropping missing values (-99.99) and using seasonally_adjusted when present.
   - Align the two series by their monthly Date index; restrict to the last 10 years (rolling window ending at the latest complete year/month in the temperature series).
   - Compute Earth-science-oriented diagnostics for the last 10 years:
       * Linear trend of temperature anomalies (°C/decade) via OLS.
       * Pearson correlation between anomalies and CO2.
       * Annual mean anomalies for each year in the last decade.

3) Modeling & forecasting:
   - Use SARIMAX with monthly seasonality (m=12). Endogenous: temperature anomalies; exogenous: CO2 (scaled).
   - Train on all but the last 12 months; validate on the final 12 months and report RMSE.
   - Forecast the next 60 months (5 years) using future CO2 extrapolation:
       * Build a simple exogenous pathway by linearly extrapolating the last 24 months of CO2 (seasonally adjusted) to 60 months ahead, preserving annual seasonality via monthly deltas from the last 24 months average.
       * Document assumptions in printed output.
   - Aggregate monthly forecasts to annual means and produce a concise table.

4) Outputs:
   - Print a summary to stdout:
       * Data coverage ranges.
       * Last-10-year temperature trend (°C/decade).
       * Correlation with CO2.
       * Validation RMSE (last 12 months).
       * Next-5-year annual mean anomaly projections.
       * Assumption notes.
   - Save files to an "outputs" directory created if missing:
       * outputs/climate_forecast_monthly.csv
       * outputs/climate_forecast_annual.csv
       * outputs/climate_trend_summary.txt (same content as stdout summary)
       * outputs/forecast_plot.png (line plot of historical anomalies and forecast with uncertainty bands if available)

5) Implementation details:
   - Use pandas, numpy, requests, statsmodels (SARIMAX), matplotlib. Avoid interactive backends; save figures.
   - Include robust error handling (network failures, schema changes). If primary temperature URL fails, try fallback. If both fail, raise a clear error. For CO2, fail with clear error if the file cannot be parsed.
   - Clearly comment steps and include docstrings at top citing datasets (NASA GISTEMP v4; NOAA GML Mauna Loa CO2) and standard references (e.g., IPCC AR6) for context.
   - Ensure reproducibility: set random seeds as needed; avoid non-deterministic paths.
   - The code should run end-to-end without user inputs.

6) Deliverables in stdout should be human-readable and concise.

inputs_used.prompt:
Write a standalone Python script that will be saved as finance/Alphabet/predict_stock.py and do the following when executed:

Requirements:
1) Create the directory finance/Alphabet if it does not already exist.
2) Fetch the last month of daily historical closing prices for Alphabet Inc (ticker: GOOGL) using yfinance. Use a reliable approach such as period="1mo" and interval="1d".
3) Preprocess the data:
   - Use only the Close column.
   - Scale values to [0,1] using MinMaxScaler.
   - Create sequences with a lookback window (e.g., 5 days) for training.
4) Build and train a small LSTM model using TensorFlow/Keras suitable for the limited data size (e.g., 1-2 LSTM layers and a Dense output). Keep epochs modest (e.g., 50 or fewer) and batch size small.
5) Predict the next 7 business days of closing prices using the trained model via iterative forecasting from the last window.
6) Prepare a combined DataFrame with columns [Date, Close, Predicted]:
   - Historical rows (from the downloaded data) should have Date and Close filled, Predicted set to NaN.
   - Future 7 business-day rows should have Date and Predicted filled, Close set to NaN.

detailed_results.task_content: Design a program that can automatically identify scam text messages and mark them as junk. Use pytho...

expected_inputs.prompt: Design a program that can automatically identify scam text messages and mark them as junk

inputs_used.prompt:
Write a Python program named 'scam_sms_filter.py' that automatically identifies scam (spam/phishing) text messages and marks them as junk. Implement the following:

1) Purpose and capabilities
- Detect likely scam/junk SMS messages using a hybrid approach: ML text classification + heuristic signals (e.g., suspicious keywords, URLs, phone numbers, currency amounts, urgency phrases).
- Provide a command-line interface (CLI) to:
  a) Train a model on a labeled CSV dataset (columns: 'label' in {"ham","spam"} and 'message').
  b) Classify new messages from a text file (one message per line) or CSV (column 'message').
  c) Mark messages classified as spam as junk by writing them to a separate output file or directory.

2) Implementation details
- Use scikit-learn with a Pipeline: TfidfVectorizer (lowercasing, English stop words, n-grams up to 2) + LinearSVC or LogisticRegression.
- Add a custom transformer HeuristicFeatures that computes additional binary/numeric features:
  * Contains URL (regex)
  * Contains phone number (regex for various formats)
  * Contains currency/amount (e.g., $, £, € with digits)
  * Contains urgency phrases (e.g., "urgent", "act now", "limited time", "verify", "suspend", "OTP")
  * Contains giveaway/lure terms (e.g., "free", "prize", "lottery", "gift", "refund")
  * Message length
- Combine TF-IDF features with heuristic features using FeatureUnion.
- Use class_weight='balanced' where applicable to handle imbalance.
- Provide evaluation during training: 5-fold cross-validation F1-score and accuracy printed.
- Save the trained model to a .joblib file.

3) CLI interface via argparse
Commands:
- Train: python scam_sms_filter.py train --data path/to/dataset.csv --model path/to/model.joblib
- Classify: python scam_sms_filter.py classify --input path/to/messages.txt --model path/to/model.joblib --junk-out junk.txt --ham-out inbox.txt
- Classify CSV: python scam_sms_filter.py classify --input path/to/messages.csv --model path/to/model.joblib --junk-out junk.csv --ham-out inbox.csv --csv

Behavior:
- For 'train', load dataset, build pipeline, evaluate with cross-val, fit on full data, save model.
- For 'classify', load model, read messages from input file. If --csv is given, read the 'message' column; else treat each line as one message.
- Predict labels; write spam predictions to junk output file and ham predictions to ham output file, preserving the message text and optionally prediction score/decision function.
- Print a summary: counts of spam vs ham.

4) Code structure
- main() function with subparsers for 'train' and 'classify'.
- Robust input validation and helpful error messages.
- Logging at INFO level.
- Functions:
  * load_dataset_csv(path)
  * build_pipeline()
  * train_and_evaluate(df)
  * save_model(pipeline, path)
  * load_model(path)
  * read_messages(path, is_csv)
  * classify_messages(messages, model)
  * write_classification_results(messages, labels, junk_out, ham_out, is_csv)

5) Dependencies
- scikit-learn, joblib, pandas (optional but recommended), numpy, regex module (re).
- No external cloud services; offline classification.

6) Notes
- Assume dataset uses labels 'ham' and 'spam'.
- Use sensible defaults; raise errors on missing files.
- Include clear docstrings and usage examples in the code header.
- Keep code self-contained and ready to run.

Create a program that optimizes the CPU usage of a given program?

expected_inputs.prompt: Create a program that optimizes the CPU usage of a given program.

inputs_used.prompt:
Create a robust, cross-platform Python program named cpu_optimizer.py that optimizes the CPU usage of a target process. The script should:

1) Overview and Features
- Accept either an existing process PID or a command to launch a program.
- Offer optimization modes:
  - reduce: lower CPU usage by throttling (target CPU percentage), lower process priority, and optionally restrict CPU affinity.
  - maximize: increase performance by raising priority and enabling full CPU affinity; no throttling.
  - balance: medium priority; optional light throttling if requested.
- Provide options to set target CPU percentage, control interval/period, adjust CPU affinity, set process priority, and choose whether to include child processes.
- Be safe and resilient: handle permission errors, non-supported features (e.g., affinity on macOS), process termination, KeyboardInterrupt, and cleanly resume the process on exit.
- Cross-platform: Windows, Linux, and macOS. Use psutil for common operations, and fallbacks when not supported.

2) Dependencies and Instructions
- Use standard library + psutil. Include a clear note that the user must `pip install psutil`.
- Provide command-line help and examples.

3) Implementation Details
- Argparse options:
  * mutually exclusive: --pid PID or --cmd "command with args"
  * --mode {reduce,maximize,balance} (default: reduce)
  * --target-cpu (int, 1-100; default 50) only meaningful for reduce/balance modes
  * --interval (float; default 0.5) control period in seconds for throttle duty cycling
  * --affinity (comma-separated list of CPU core indices; optional)
  * --priority {low,normal,high,realtime} (default varies by mode)
  * --include-children (flag) to apply actions to child processes recursively
  * --duration (float; optional) to limit optimizer run time in seconds
  * --no-throttle (flag) to disable throttling in balance/reduce modes
- Process acquisition:
  * If --pid provided: attach to existing process via psutil.Process.
  * If --cmd provided: launch with subprocess.Popen, then wrap with psutil.Process.
- Priority setting:
  * Windows: use psutil priority classes: IDLE_PRIORITY_CLASS for low, NORMAL_PRIORITY_CLASS for normal, HIGH_PRIORITY_CLASS for high, REALTIME_PRIORITY_CLASS for realtime (guard with permissions). Fall back gracefully if setting fails.
  * POSIX (Linux/macOS): use os.setpriority(os.PRIO_PROCESS, pid, nice_value): low=10, normal=0, high=-10, realtime=-15 (guard with permissions; mac may not allow negative nice without root).
- CPU affinity:
  * Only supported on Linux/Windows with psutil; check support and print a warning if not available. If --affinity provided, set that list; If maximize mode and no affinity provided, set to all cores.
- Throttle controller using psutil suspend/resume duty cycling:
  * Implement a ThrottleController that uses a duty cycle per interval: run for interval * duty (duty = target_cpu/100), then suspend for interval * (1-duty). This approximates limiting average CPU usage for CPU-bound processes.
  * Use psutil.Process.suspend()/resume(); if include-children is set, apply to each child recursively. Ensure that on exit or error, processes are resumed.
  * Ensure the controller checks if proc is alive; exit gracefully if it terminates.
- Logging:
  * Provide informative prints: mode chosen, priority/affinity changes, throttle activity, warnings on unsupported features, and exit cleanup.

4) Code Structure
- Functions:
  * parse_args()
  * get_process(pid=None, cmd=None)
  * set_priority(proc, level)
  * set_affinity(proc, cores)
  * iter_process_tree(proc, include_children)
  * resume_all(procs); suspend_all(procs)
- Class:
  * ThrottleController(proc, target_cpu, interval, include_children)
    - method: run(max_duration=None)
- main(): parse args, get process, apply priority/affinity based on mode, optionally create and run ThrottleController, wait until duration or Ctrl+C.
- Provide if __name__ == "__main__": main()

5) Examples printed in --help:
- python cpu_optimizer.py --pid 12345 --mode reduce --target-cpu 40 --interval 0.5 --priority low --affinity 0,1 --include-children
- python cpu_optimizer.py --cmd "python heavy_task.py --opt x" --mode maximize --priority high
- python cpu_optimizer.py --pid 3456 --mode balance --target-cpu 60 --duration 120

6) Safety & Cleanup
- Ensure that any suspended processes are resumed on exit (KeyboardInterrupt or errors).
- Handle cases where affinity or priority changes are not permitted.

Write the full, runnable Python code, with docstrings and helpful comments. Ensure all imports are present, and the script is clear and maintainable.

expected_inputs.prompt: Given an existing Python script that performs heavy numeric computations in loops, produce an optimized version using NumPy vectorization and, where beneficial, multiprocessing (or concurrent.futures) for CPU-bound work. Include clear function docstrings, type hints, and brief inline comments explaining the vectorized transformations. Also provide a small benchmark snippet comparing the original loop implementation vs. the optimized version on synthetic data. Avoid unnecessary dependencies beyond numpy.

inputs_used.prompt:
Task: Produce an optimized, production-ready rewrite of an existing Python module named 'heavy_numeric_computations.py' focusing on vectorization and parallel programming.

Requirements:
- Use NumPy vectorization extensively (broadcasting, einsum/matmul, reduction ops, stride tricks, FFT where suitable) to eliminate Python loops.
- Optionally accelerate hot loops with Numba (njit with parallel=True, fastmath=True) when beneficial; include runtime feature detection and pure-NumPy fallbacks.
- Provide parallelization options for CPU-bound independent workloads using concurrent.futures.ProcessPoolExecutor. Design chunking strategies to control memory pressure and maximize cache efficiency.
- Implement numerically stable operations (e.g., stable softmax with max-shift and clipping of small negatives before sqrt).
- Ensure careful memory management: preallocate arrays, use in-place operations when safe, avoid unnecessary copies, and provide block-size/chunk-size parameters for large data.
- Include clear docstrings, type hints, sane default parameters, and minimal external dependencies (only numpy, numba if available, and standard library). No heavy external libraries.
- Provide a small benchmarking/demo under if __name__ == "__main__": that demonstrates usage and compares vectorized vs parallel implementations on synthetic data.
- Export a clean API via __all__.

Module contents to implement:
1) pairwise_distances(X: np.ndarray, Y: np.ndarray, *, chunk_size: int | None = None, use_numba: bool = False) -> np.ndarray
   - Compute Euclidean pairwise distances between rows of X (shape [m, d]) and Y (shape [n, d]).
   - Vectorized approach using ||x||^2 + ||y||^2 - 2 X @ Y^T, then clip negatives before sqrt.
   - Optional chunked computation when memory is constrained (process Y in blocks).
   - Optional Numba kernel for squared distances when use_numba=True.

2) batched_matmul(A: np.ndarray, B: np.ndarray, *, use_numba: bool = False) -> np.ndarray
   - Multiply two batches: A shape [b, m, k], B shape [b, k, n]. Prefer np.matmul/einsum.
   - Optional Numba parallel loop fallback for very large b.

3) rolling_mean_std(x: np.ndarray, window: int) -> tuple[np.ndarray, np.ndarray]
   - Compute rolling mean and std over a 1D array using stride tricks for vectorization.
   - Validate window and handle edge cases.

4) softmax_stable(x: np.ndarray, *, axis: int = -1) -> np.ndarray
   - Numerically stable softmax using max-shift and exp normalization.

5) convolve2d(image: np.ndarray, kernel: np.ndarray, *, mode: str = "same") -> np.ndarray
   - Implement 2D convolution using FFT for large kernels; fall back to direct method for small kernels.
   - No external libraries beyond numpy.

6) monte_carlo_pi(n_samples: int, *, n_workers: int | None = None, chunk_size: int | None = None, seed: int | None = None) -> float
   - Estimate pi via Monte Carlo, supporting parallel chunk execution using ProcessPoolExecutor.
   - Ensure deterministic seeding when provided.

7) gradient_descent_step(X: np.ndarray, y: np.ndarray, w: np.ndarray, *, lr: float, l2: float = 0.0) -> np.ndarray
   - Single gradient descent step for linear regression with optional L2 regularization, fully vectorized.

8) Utility helpers: chunk_indices(total: int, chunk_size: int) -> list[tuple[int, int]];
   maybe_parallel_map(func, chunks, max_workers) to help parallel Monte Carlo.

9) Runtime feature detection for Numba and conditional JIT implementations (e.g., pairwise squared distances for the kernel).

10) __main__ demo: Generate synthetic data, benchmark pairwise_distances (vectorized vs chunked vs numba), batched_matmul, rolling stats, softmax, convolution, Monte Carlo, and gradient step.

Implementation notes:
- Use type hints and docstrings for all functions.
- Carefully guard imports: try to import numba; set HAS_NUMBA flag accordingly.
- For Numba implementations, keep signatures simple and rely on prange for parallel loops; prefer contiguous arrays (np.ascontiguousarray) and validate dtypes (float32/float64).
- For pairwise distances, avoid forming huge intermediate matrices when memory is tight: implement chunked version over Y blocks; precompute norms for X and for each Y block.
- In 2D convolution, if kernel and image are large (e.g., min(image.shape + kernel.shape) > threshold), use FFT-based convolution with zero-padding; otherwise, use a direct sliding-window method.
- For rolling stats, use numpy.lib.stride_tricks.as_strided to create a windowed view; compute mean/std along axis 1. Keep behavior similar to 'valid' mode (no padding).
- Ensure functions raise informative ValueError for invalid shapes/arguments.
- Keep the module self-contained and importable.

expected_inputs.prompt: quantum computing problem to calculate amplitude, probability, optimize with simulated annealing, and visualize results

inputs_used.prompt:
Create a deterministic Python script named quantum_computing.py that:

1) Defines an amplitude function for a given qubit configuration x in {0,1}^n:
   - Number of qubits: n = 6
   - Fixed weights: w = [0.5, 0.8, 1.0, 0.6, 0.9, 0.7]
   - Phases set to zero for determinism. Use A(x) = sum_i w_i * (-1)**x_i.

2) Defines the probability of a configuration x as p(x) = |A(x)|^2 / Z, where Z is the normalization constant obtained by summing |A(x)|^2 over all VALID configurations.

3) Constraints (VALID configuration):
   - Hamming weight (number of ones) <= 2
   - No adjacent ones (i.e., for any i, not both x_i == 1 and x_{i+1} == 1)

4) Implements simulated annealing to maximize p(x) subject to the constraints:
   - Random seed = 42 for reproducibility
   - Initial temperature T0 = 5.0, cooling rate alpha = 0.995, iterations = 10000
   - Start from a random valid configuration
   - Neighbor: flip a single randomly chosen bit, only accept if the resulting configuration meets constraints; if the chosen flip violates constraints, retry up to a few times; if no valid neighbor is found, resample a neighbor
   - Metropolis acceptance: accept if new probability is higher or with probability exp((p_new - p_old)/T)
   - Track and output the best configuration and its probability

5) Also compute and print:
   - The amplitude and probability of a target configuration target = '000000'
   - The best configuration and probability found by simulated annealing

6) Implementation notes:
   - Use only Python standard library (e.g., random, math, itertools) and keep the program self-contained
   - Enumerate all valid states to compute Z exactly for normalization
   - Provide clear printouts of results and a summary at the end
   - Ensure deterministic results by maintaining the random seed and using the fixed weights
   - Include docstrings and comments indicating the approach and that the code was generated by Grok-3

The final script should print the following:
- Amplitude for target state
- Probability for target state (normalized)
- Best configuration from simulated annealing
- Maximum probability found

Save the file as quantum_computing.py.
